==English==
===Interjection===
'''gardyloo'''
#  Used to warn passers-by of waste about to be thrown from a window into the street below.
===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''gare l'eau'' which means "beware of the water."
gardaloo was a word used by the french in the middle ages through the renaissance.  It was yelled out of a window to warn passersby of a chamber pot about to be emptied from said window.  Gardyloo was a very important term to remember in case you were to get hit by some flying waste.

